fields.description:
When a plugin developer creates a custom result tab following the available documentation, the gui is broken when switching between jobs.  The url is not properly updated when query strings are used for custom actions.  The javascript used to update the links in the Plan Navigator assumes that the url will contain the buildResultKey ($plankKey-$buildKey-$buildNumber) but this is not the case when using query strings which take the form of buildKey=${buildKey}&buildNumber=${buildNumber}.

jshap999 said: 

{quote}Possible areas for addressing this would be in how the javascript does the replace, using the buildResultKey for resultaware actions in conjunction with separate buildKey and buildNumber or providing plugin developers a way to create more RESTful urls like the way built in actions are mapped.{quote}

jshap999 said: 

{quote}My javascript change:

{code}
            if ($planNavigator.length) {
                // Update urls in plan navigator
                if (activeJobKey) {
                    // Update job urls
                    $jobs.each(function () {
                        var $li = $(this),
                            $a = $li.children('a').last(),
                            jobKey = $li.attr('data-job-key'),
                            jobKeyParts = jobKey.split("-", 4),   
                            buildKey = jobKeyParts[0] + "-" + jobKeyParts[1] + "-" + jobKeyParts[2],        
                            activeJobKeyParts = activeJobKey.split("-", 4),  
                            activeBuildKey = activeJobKeyParts[0] + "-" + activeJobKeyParts[1] + "-" + activeJobKeyParts[2];
                        
                        if(jobKey != activeJobKey)
                        {    
                            url = url.replace(activeBuildKey, buildKey);
                            url = url.replace(activeJobKey, jobKey);
                        }    
                        $a.attr('href', url);
                    });
                } else {
                    // Update plan url
                    $plan.children('a').attr('href', url);
                }
            }
{code}{quote}

Created from https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/BAM-11300

When DefaultXStreamManager marshalls TreeMap instance, it looks like this:
{code:xml}
<spotPriceMap class="net.sf.hibernate.collection.SortedMap">
  <!-- content not relevant -->
</spotPriceMap>
{code}

This is caused by
{code:title=HibernateDefaultImplementationInitializer}
    @Override
    public void initialize(XStream xStream)
    {
        ...
        xStream.addDefaultImplementation(TreeMap.class, net.sf.hibernate.collection.SortedMap.class);
        ...
    }
{code}
but I'm unsure if that can be simply removed.

Basically I think we use ".addDefaultImplementation" not according to it's designed purpose.

Consider following scenario:

script.sh in my repo:
{code}
echo $BAMBOO_BUILDNUMBER
{code}

Bamboo plan consisting of a single ScriptTask, which calls 'script.sh' from my repo. What happens? AFAIK the BAMBOO_BUILDNUMBER will be blank, where we would, tfu, Jenkins users could expect that BAMBOO_BUILDNUMBER will be some #no.
Note the $BAMBOO_BUILDNUMBER is environment variable, not the {noformat}${bamboo.buildNumber} {noformat}

This is contrary to our 'casual' plan/global variables (user created), which are injected into environment. If you create plan variable "plan.variable = 50", then calling script containing
{code}
echo $BAMBOO_PLAN_VARIABLE
{code}
will result in displaying 50. At least AFAIK.

Does it make sense?

In order to know which variable name to use for an executable, one must click on that executable from Server Capabilities and check the last part of the URL. For example, after adding a Command capability, and clicking on that capability, the last part of the URL is: "capabilityKey=system.builder.command.test". The correct Variable name for accessing the value of that executable is:  ${bamboo.capability.system.builder.command.test}

This is confusing, and it would be great to improve the UI to indicate this information.

After improving the UI, we also need to improve [the documentation|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/BAMBOO/Using+global,+plan+or+build-specific+variables#Usingglobal,planorbuild-specificvariables-Specifyingcapabilitiesasvariables] that corresponds to this part

I may already have a workaround for this, but the intent here is around a workflow where artifacts are published to a central repository, in this case Maven; 

The primary plan runs against the development line and drops -SNAPSHOT builds to maven, and should automatically do so; however, a release branch should have the mvn deploy call be a manual step to allow for review.

Another example of where this would be useful is for situations where a development build publishes to a development server, but a production build should pause before deployment to the production server - deployment location is parameterized to allow variation in the final location.

Accessing the agent matrix link from the Agents page by clicking on the "matrix" link in:

{quote}
You can also use this matrix to determine which agents can execute which build plans.
{quote}

brings me to a blank page. However, accessing the Agent Matrix link from the left side of the admin section works.

Add a feature to allow saving the remote agent configuration details in the REMOTE_AGENT_HOME/conf/wrapper.conf file during the first time installation of the remote agent. For example, if a user tries to install a remote agent and adds command line options for the first time, add them to the wrapper.conf:
{code}
java -Dwrapper.java.additional.3=-Djavax.net.ssl.keyStorePassword=changeit -Dwrapper.java.maxmemory=1024 -jar atlassian-bamboo-agent-installer-4.3.3.jar http://127.0.0.1:8085/bamboo/agentServer/
{code}
